library(corrplot)
corrplot(cor(training_data),method='number')  # visualizes feature correlation

Analyzing the above correlation & pairwise scatter plots, we can infer many things

  • features like v11,V12,v13,v14 are least correlated to the Target so they can be ignored for all practical purposes.

  • pairs like (V13, V14) have high correlation which indicates that these pairs of features are redundant and hence, one feature in the pair will contribute very less (its coefficient will be very low) and the other will contribute high.

  • data does not suffer from multicollinearity i.e.independent variables are not highly correlated so applying Regression Regularisation techniques like Ridge, Lassso & ElasticNet wont be much useful (used in case of multicollinearity).

SIMPLE LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL - MODEL 0
 (Only 1 independent variable chosen)

r <- -1
for(i in 2:17){
  training_data1 <- training_data[,c(1,i)]
  model <- lm(Target ~ ., data = training_data1) # uses 1 independent variables at a time
  a <- summary(model)$adj.r.squared
  if(r < a){
    r <- a
    m <- model
  }
}
model <- m
print(summary(model))

  validation_data_1 <- cbind(validation_data, Predicted = predicted_values)
  validation_data_1 <- validation_data_1[,c(1, 18, 2:17)]
  return(validation_data_1)
}

DECISION TREE - MODEL 4

training_data_new <- training_data
validation_data <- read.csv("D2 - Validation Dataset.csv", row.names = 1)

adj.r.sq <- function(r.sq, n, p){ # n = sample size, p = no. of predictors
  adj.r <- 1 - ((1-r.sq)*(n-1)/(n-p-1))
  return (adj.r)
}

library (party)
# library(partykit)
library(caret)

fit <- ctree (Target ~ ., training_data_new)  # build the tree model
#print(fit)
# st <- as.simpleparty(fit)
# plot(st)
tree_pred <- predict(fit, validation_data)
#mean((tree_pred - validation_data[,"Target"])^2) # mse of 15528880796 which is even lower
prs <- postResample(pred = tree_pred, obs = validation_data[,"Target"])
adj.r <- adj.r.sq(prs["Rsquared"], nrow(validation_data), 9)     # 0.5370369, 0.5531
adj.r <- round(adj.r, 4)
rmse <- prs["RMSE"]   # 124614.9, 122338.5
rmse <- round(rmse, 4)
paste("Adjusted R^2 value for Decision Tree:",adj.r, sep = " ")
## [1] "Adjusted R^2 value for Decision Tree: 0.537"
paste("Root Mean Square Error for Decision Tree:",format(rmse), sep = " ")
## [1] "Root Mean Square Error for Decision Tree: 124614.9"
plot (fit, main="Conditional Inference Tree")  # the ctree

model4 <- c(rmse, adj.r)
df1 <- df
df1 <- df1[-3,]
df1 <- df1[,-c(2,3)]
df1 <- cbind(df1, "Decision Tree" = model4)
df1[1,3] <- format(round(df1[1,3], 0))
colnames(df1) <- c("Simple Linear Regression", "Stepwise Regression with NO outliers", "Decision Tree")
Model wise Diagnostics
Simple Linear Regression Stepwise Regression with NO outliers Decision Tree
Root Mean Square Error 168000 146000 124615

It can be inferred that Decision Tree is the best model among the three shown above. Simple Linear Regression is too simple/underfitting for the data which is also clear by the fact that it has the highest RMSE. Decision Tree has the lowest RMSE. Its Adjusted \(R^{2}\) value is just written for a reference; Adjusted \(R^{2}\) value is not a good performance metric for a decision tree so its not considered usually.
